mily:Arial; font-size:12pt"> investigations into bullying must be conducted by an external organisation. The BBC should not be allowed to investigate the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How well has th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e BBC performed in the current c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">harter period in achieving i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ts mission and public purposes? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">public pur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">poses in the current c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">harter the right ones? How m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> they change?</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s public purposes are: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sustaining citizenship and civil society; promoting education and learning; stimulating creativity and cultural excellence; representing the UK, its nations, r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egions and communities; bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK; and promoting its other purposes, helping to deliver to the public the benefit of emerging communications technologies and services and, in addition, taking a leading role in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> switchover to digital television.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NUJ believes the public purposes in the current charter are the right </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ones,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> however it may be helpful to add a recognition of the BBC and its contribution to the creative economy and its responsibility as a training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the whole industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. There should also be a responsibility for the corporation as part of its public purpose, to acknowledge its role in promoting and representing equality and diversity as an employer and in its programming and reach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to all sectors of society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The NUJ believes the BBC has performed well in its mission and public purpose. With shows such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Strictly Come Dancing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The British Great Bake Off </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Dr Who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it has high ratings and mainstream appeal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sherlock Holm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, Lu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ther </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Top of the Lake</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provides</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> innovative drama and BBC4 has a rich diet of quality documentaries. Its news co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">verage remains of high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quality,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lthough the NUJ is concerned cuts to news are not sustainable. Its coverage of the Olympics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">praised around the world</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, redeeming the corporation's reputation following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> much-criticised coverage of the Queen's Diamond Jubilee.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC also produced the wonderfully funny </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Twenty Twelve,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which showed that could satirise as well as celebrate the Oly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mpics without causing offence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC's output and services must reflect the needs of all licence-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fee payers. However, this should be seen in the context of its public purposes. Unlike commercial broadcasters, it needs to ensure that all regions are covered and also has to ensure there is quality programming and a commitment to news coverage across the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> UK and overseas. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The BBC should continue to provide a rich diet of populist and niche programming. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The BBC has faced criticism that its focus is London and South-east centric: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hopefully the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> move to Salford</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and other regional deployments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will rectify this.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The NUJ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disagrees with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> claim that the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is damaging local media. However, the union believes that the corporation should make more effort to promote the source of its local news, for example by providing links to the original newspaper/website and if it uses local expertise it should give credi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t for it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is healthy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that external companies bid to produce output</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> equally important that standards are maintained. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Quality will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> compromise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if commissions go to only the lowest price. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC already plays a significant role as a stimulator of the creative economy as a commissioner of independent produces, through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the 25 per cent quota and the window of creative opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (WOC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The NUJ believes the present balance is about right and would argue for the status quo.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a need for the BBC to retain in-house production and make local programmes across the nat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ions and regions. Local identity is important and it is essential the BBC is not seen just as south east England orientated. Drama, films and culture reflect the variety across the nations and regions and should predominantly be delivered through the BBC p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roduction although a small percentage of independent commissions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> acceptable.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s training budget has been reduced by 20 per cent; this will have a significant impact on the development of the profession, especially in the nations and regions. How</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ever, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">casualisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> throughout the industry is already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">having an effect on the pool of experience in investigative journalism. The nurturing of staff by the most experienced people on a team no longer happens. Even the most experienced BBC investigative re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">porters are now freelance and therefore are not responsible for training junior staff, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are there only for a few months at a time while working on a single production. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is important because of the significance BBC training has to the whole industry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Many TV production companies are small, and do not have the capacity to provide training, and many rely upon staff who have benefited from BBC training.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How have the BBC’s commercial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> activities during the current c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">harter fitted with the BBC’s public purpo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ses and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> of such activities beyond </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2016.</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What Lonely Planet is the BBC on?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This was one of the headlines following the news that the BBC lost almost £10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0 million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> after </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its disastrous acquisition of the backpackers' guide by Worldwide, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e corporation's commercial arm.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC should do what it does best – making programme and content. Sales based on these activities should be pursued but the BBC must lear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n from this blunder and should resist similar ventures.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NUJ is concerned by the creeping commercialisation of the BBC. It intends to partly offset the cuts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maximising profits from the BBC’s commercial subsidiary, BBC Worldwide, which raised cash </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">totalling £1.09bn in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through selling programmes to networks in other countries, as well as through publishing ventures and organising promotional tours. However, only a minority stake is now retained in ventures such as BBC Books (now majority owned b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y Random House Group), BBC Children’s Books (now 75 per cent owned by Penguin Books) and BBC Active learning resources (now majority owned by Pearson plc).The most concerning aspect of this renewed emphasis on commercialisation is the incursion of the prof</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it motive into editorial and newsgathering priorities. Peter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Horrocks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, director of BBC Global News (which includes the World Service)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reportedly told journalists they would be required to come up with ideas “to strengthen our commercial focus and grow inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ome” as part of their job appraisals.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other BBC managers in news, online and radio are reported as setting similar agendas</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If a newsroom has to become entrepreneurial in this way, then the potential to sell on a story for profit takes priority over servin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g the public interest. This comes hard on the heels of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scandal which saw the BBC forced to issue an apology for broadcasting documentaries on Malaysia after it was given £17m by the Malaysian government for “global strategic communications”. It al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">so broadcast material on Egypt made by FBC Media (UK), a PR firm working for the Mubarak regime. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">'s relationship with technology is somewhat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">checke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ever it has, in the past, been a key player in the development of innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the industry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><a href="http://www.radioplayer.co.uk/"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Radioplayer</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are good example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of this and the corporation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should continue to use its expertise to develop new ways to distribute content.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This, however, should be properly f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inanced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016? Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he BBC?</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NUJ believes the licence fee should be maintained and increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at least in line with inflation. At</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 40 pence a day, it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">extremely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">great value</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the huge range of services it provides.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Director general Tony Hall, in his speech in November to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Voice of the Listener </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Viewer Conference, spelled out this value for money. He said:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"Twenty years ago, the BBC received nearly 40 per cent of all the revenues in broadcasting. Now the figure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is around a quarter – 25 per cent - a much smaller part of the media market. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wenty years ago we were the largest broadcasting organisation. Now we are not.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Twenty years ago, the licence fee was over £147 in today’s money – now it’s a bit lower. But look w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat you </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">get.Twenty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> years ago, we had two TV stations, five national radio stations, and local and Nations radio. Now we deliver so much more with four times more television channels, twice as many national radio stations, impressive web services and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">layer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The present fee agreement was reached</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in October 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> following a behind-closed doors deal between the Department for Culture Media and Sport and the then BBC director general, Mark Thompson. The CMS select committee said </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the deal "undermined confidence in both the government's and the BBC's commitment to transparency and accountability and should not be repeated". The freezing of the licence fee until 2017 led </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the cost-cutting programme D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a 20 per cent cut to the BBC’s budget and loss of 2,000 jobs, on top of the 7,000 lost since 2004. More than 5,000 jobs went under Mark Thompson's Value for Money cost-cutting exercise. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These cuts were made while the BBC was taking on extra £340 millio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n extra spending responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> including the World Service, S4C, funding the rollout of super-fast broadband, local TV and BBC Monitoring. Last year 140 jobs went in BBC news </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the eighth consecutive year of cuts. Investigative journalism and politic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al coverage were immediately hit. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">udit Office </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ublic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ccounts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommittee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have pointed out the BBC has not assessed what effect the cuts and efficiency savings will have on quality. The NUJ is seriously concerned that the current licence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has already had a negative impact on quality, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will continue to do so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as cuts continue.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> These were seen as contributory to the mistakes made by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Newsnight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-s