e first year – i.e. the current fina</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncial year - we will achieve £25 million of annual savings. The changes that we are implementing today are intended to hit our budget targets for the second year – 2014-15 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and will save a further £11 million. We will therefore need to find further substa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntial savings over the following two years."</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NUJ believes that the decision-making process around the next licence fee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">harter should be fully transparent and involve both parliament and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the licence fee paying public. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We call for the publication o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f all communications between the government and New</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> International and other media that refer to the BBC in the 18 months before and 6 months after the previous lic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ence fee deal in October 2010. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In view of the complete lack of a transparent process at that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> time, this is the only way to be certain that no improper influence or collusion was involved.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">According to research conducted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">between 30</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">September–18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">October 2013,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the UK is a global leader on overall TV quality, with 72 per cent of UK adults saying its TV programmes are good quality – the highest out of 14 surveyed countries </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(Australia, Brazil, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Neth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erlands, Spain, Sweden, Portugal, UK, United Arab Emirates and USA) with a representative sample of 500 adults 18+ per country (Brazil and United Arab Emirates – urban sample)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Out of 66 channels, BBC One received the highest quality score of all – with 79</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> per cent of UK adults rating it as good quality. BBC Two came third</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a public service broadcaster, the BBC has a responsibility to the licence-fee payer in terms of value for money and in full transparency in terms of its spending. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NAO revealed that £25 million was spent on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">severance payments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for 150 senior BBC manag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ers. They received on average £164,200. It concluded that weak governance arrangements led to payments that exceeded contractual entitlements, provided poor value for money and put public trust at risk. The BBC was forced to write off its Digital Media Ini</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tiative project, costing almost £100 million. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the BBC was making journalists redundant and cutting programmes as part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its economies,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it spent £8.2 million on management consultants for "change management" services in 2011. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This situation was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cau</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sed by the top of the organisation being totally disconnected from</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the journalists and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">progr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">amme makers at the corporation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That is why the NUJ believes that staff should be members of the BBC's Trust. All of the things that went wrong raised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alarm bells with staff at the time – but nobody listened</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Spending quotas across the nations and regions need to be equitably delivered and representative, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that is why </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">democratic input is essential.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC Trust should include members' organisations from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ivil society, the industry and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> trade unions and not just the great and the good. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> TUC report showed there are 16 EU countries where workers have a formal role at management board level or works councils. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more open, democratic Trust would provide bette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r scrutiny and would be more representative of the licence fee-paying public.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 22.5pt 25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 22.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>